choices.text: a crucial option for women. I conduct an empirical analysis of the preferences for abortion among twenty-seven Austrian askers who I interview in more than twenty provinces in Austria. My analysis is based on an experimental survey of the set of discrete choice questions where I assign preferences for pro-choice rights conditional on the availability of the instrument. My analysis can also be considered as the data collection of a ‘natural experiment’. This question is raised from the perspective of science and people in Austria through an experiment of Boyer et al. (2015) regarding the preferences of natural experiment participants. Accordingly, only pro-life askers do not recommend keeping access to induced abortion in Austria. In this paper, I examine the attitudes of pro-choice askers towards legal universally limited induced abortion as opposed to abortion options. I do not directly compare abortion types due to my study design. My study displays the preferences of twenty-seven Austrian askers towards the unavailability of induced abortion in Austria. My study uses the set of discrete choice questions for determining the respondents' preferences for the consequences of induced abortion on a five-point Likert scale (ranging from 1 - Strongly agree to 5 - Strongly disagree). My study reports the experimental observations in regression analysis by specifying a random coefficient logit model. The results suggest that the age of the respondents and the distance of the candidates' residence from the capital city are insignificant predictors of the respondents' attitudes towards the abortion situation in Austria behind natural barter.
